cs.NI, cs.IT, cs.MM, cs.SY, cs.CR 

Reasoning: 

1. cs.NI (Networking and Internet Architecture) - The paper focuses on enabling simultaneous transmit and receive (STR) mode in IEEE 802.11 WLANs, which is a networking and internet architecture topic. 

2. cs.IT (Information Theory) - The paper proposes a novel solution that leverages carrier sense multiple access with enhanced collision avoidance (CSMA/ECA) and adaptive sensitivity control mechanisms, which are information theory concepts. 

3. cs.MM (Multimedia) - The paper discusses the optimization of secondary bi-directional full-duplex (BFD) and uni-directional full-duplex (UFD) transmissions, which can be related to multimedia applications that require high bandwidth and low latency. 

4. cs.SY (Systems and Control) - The paper proposes a solution that involves co-existence and compatibility with legacy nodes and protocols, which can be related to systems and control topics. 

5. cs.CR (Cryptography and Security) - Although the paper does not explicitly discuss cryptography and security, enabling STR mode in 802.11 WLANs may have implications for security and privacy, which can be related to cryptography and security topics.
